      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To address the query structure warning, you can use parameterized queries directly in the string, without creating a separate `query` variable. Here's the refactored code:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef get_user_data(user_id: int) -> tuple:\n    \"\"\"Retrieve a user's data by their ID.\"\"\"\n    with sqlite3.connect('users.db') as conn:\n        cursor = conn.cursor()\n        query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?\"\n        cursor.execute(query, (user_id,))\n        return cursor.fetchone()\n```\n\nAlternatively, you can use f-strings (introduced in Python 3.6) to concatenate the query and parameters in a clear way, avoiding any potential syntax errors:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef get_user_data(user_id: int) -> tuple:\n    \"\"\"Retrieve a user's data by their ID.\"\"\"\n    with sqlite3.connect('users.db') as conn:\n        cursor = conn.cursor()\n        query = f\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = {user_id}\"\n        cursor.execute(query)\n        return cursor.fetchone()\n```\n\nHowever, following the former approach still provides the best practice and avoids potential issues.",
